TRIP COMMENTS: Louis Bevier, Brittany O'Connor, Larry Sansone, and I searched for the Falcated Duck, mainly from observation deck at the beginning of the auto tour route but then driving this loop.  We later scanned one of these same ponds from the north side from a pullout along State Highway 20, and finally, we scanned some flooded ponds along the southern end of the refuge from Abel Road after being told by refuge personnel that "Tule" Greater White-fronted can be found here.  We never did find the Falcated Duck, but we saw numbers of both geese and ducks that were so large that it was very difficult even to make reasonable estimates.  We arrived to partly cloudy skies with a 40% cover of high, thin clouds, a trace (<5 knot) breeze from the north-northwest, and a temperature of 38 F (based on the thermometer in Larry's vehicle).  The high clouds increased over the course of our visit to a cover 85%, the breeze from the north may have reached 5 knots yet it was variable in strength, and the temperature reached 52 F by our departure.  8:10 am - 1:00 pm.----Mule Deer - 1 (I missed one or more deer seen by others).

SPECIES COMMENTS: Continued notes on the booby...--Later, I asked Danielle to describe the bird as she saw it and she admitted that she was not especially keyed in on that bird, as she was more interested in what the larger birds (eagles) were, but she said it could have been a gull, for all she knew, and that she thought it was overall lighter in color than the brownish color I described. She further confessed that she really didnt know her birds very well and had no experience with boobies.--I initially considered (and included in my report to the bird box) that it could have been a Brown Booby, which would perhaps be more likely, but I have since decided that it showed too much white above and lacked the characteristic brown bib on the underside. Having barely any experience with other boobies (a few RFBO in the Caribbean and one MABO in Hawaii), I cannot speak with any authority about their plumage variations, but the field guides seem to indicate that darker coloration in the plumage of those species are not the norm.  Size and shape of the subject bird leave me convinced that it was a sulid, and process of elimination leads me to believe that it was in fact a Blue-footed Booby. Although I was not mindfully aware of the white patch on the hind-neck as a characteristic mark for Blue-footed, it was the first and most outstanding mark I observed in the plumage of the subject bird.  While it is somewhat troubling that I did not make note of a white, U-shaped rump patch, which is another characteristic field mark for BF, I did note that in addition to the patch on the nape, there were other areas of white on the birds upperside that I just didnt have opportunity to absorb enough to describe during the observation, which lasted only about 10 seconds, under less than ideal conditions.--The Klamath River mouth is an exceptionally productive foraging area for birds. On this day, and subsequent 2 days, we observed feeding frenzies involving up to 12 Osprey and 6 Bald Eagles at once, dozens of Caspian Terns plunge-diving in the surf, hundreds of gulls, loons, grebes actively foraging, as well as seals and sea lions eating fish, three or more Gray Whales in very close, murres, murrelets, among other species.

TRIP COMMENTS: Pine Hill Preserve bird tour. Calm with thin clouds. Walked to Morning Glory Hill and back. Most notable non-bird was a Blainville's Horned Lizard. After it was first spotted, it moved to shelter under vegetation, but remained partially visible for all to see and even allowed scope views. A few of us had quick views of what was probably a California Striped Racer going across the path. Also seen were Western Tiger, Anise, and Pipevine Swallowtails, Bramble Hairstreak, Red Admiral, California Ringlet, and Painted Lady butterflies. Notable plants included Stebbins' Morning Glory, Pine Hill Ceanothus, Red Hills Soaproot, Ithuriel's Spear, Butter and Eggs, Paintbrush, Pretty Face, Popcorn Flower (sp.?), Buttercup (sp.?), Globe Lilly (or Fairy Lantern), and Mallow (sp.?). Joined by Kimya this year.

Sacramento Audubon field trip led by Andi Salmi. Weather was mostly heavy overcast, a bit unsettled with periods of light drizzle, but with only a light breeze. Temperatures in the low 60's F. Estimates of waterfowl are based largely on impressions and are mainly significant as a way to represent relative abundance. Due to the severe drought, available water was limited and waterfowl were concentrated in those areas fortunate enough to have water. Estimates are also compromised by the restriction of having to stay within vehicles and thus scoping waterfowl over a broad range was not possible. --

TRIP COMMENTS: COVERAGE: Stationary Count looking down on Isabella Reservoir from pull-out along South Fork Kern River watershed side of Sierra Way a little before reaching the pass over into the North Fork Kern River watershed. TEMPERATURE: 71 degrees Fahrenheit.
SPECIES COMMENTS: adult continued. Perched on a tree snag on the exposed portion of the reservoir 50-100 yard away from the current shoreline. Large raptor with an all dark body, all white head, all white tail, yellow bill. An adult of this species has been found at this location several times since mid-May.
were both adults. This is the first time this summer that two Bald Eagles have been seen at isabella Reservoir.
the continuing summering adult Bald Eagle is observed again at the mouth of the North Fork of the Kern River
Bald Eagle: single adult perched in North Fork Delta snag early this morning.
were both adults

An update on the Bald Eagles: Two adults observed on 8 Sept; one observed on 9 Sept.  Both observations are in the North Fork Delta area.  Very good views had of the lone bird this morning (9 Sept) and I was able to determine it to be an "almost adult".  Bird exhibits a very faint smudgy eye-line and smudgy mottling in the crown. The rectrices are mainly white but most show irregular blackish tips, with one central rectrix showing a lot of blackish mottling.  Some white spotting in the wing linings also. This doesn't mean that an attempt at breeding didn't occur in the valley, so I am still actively looking for young birds.
two adults and one fresh juvenile. Possible 2nd juvenile. Fresh juvenile intriguing as it suggests local nesting.

LOCALITY: Frank G. Bonelli RP/Puddingstone Reservoir and vicinity
SPECIES COMMENTS: I was driving north on the 57 Freeway when an immature Bald Eagle was soaring eastbound,towards Bonelli Park. The bird's size was impressive, compared to the Red-tailed Hawks that soar over these same hills, regularly. Its wings were proportionately long. The wings were very straight, unlike those of a Golden Eagle, that looks like an oversized Red-tailed Hawk. The wings were held very straight outwards, to the sides, with no dihedral. The bird had some mottled white diffuse all over the bird, not the well-defined wing and tail patches of a Golden Eagle. Also, the bird's head and tail stuck out of the body in equal proportions, unlike a Golden Eagle, that would look long tailed, and small headed.

Stopped about 3/4 mile south of the junction with the road to Mill Creek Falls Campground where there is a good view down onto flooded fields and creek channels. Four River Otters foraging as a group in these channels were a surprising treat. In a single binocular view, without panning, I could briefly view these 4, plus a pair of Sandhill Cranes, plus several Black Terns dipping low over the same water. Gotta love Modoc birding!

TRIP COMMENTS: Again helping Nancy Kenyon (along with Neal Anderson) in Nancy's area for the Northeastern Orange County Christmas Bird Count (CBC)--Irvine Lake and vicinity.  WEATHER:  Lost the original notes on which I'd written weather for the day, so well after the fact I wrote: "I recall (somewhat vaguely) that it wasn't too cold in the early morning hours. Mild temps and wind, so very decent weather. There was a fair amount of mud here and there, as it had rained a bit over the last couple days.  NOTES:  Even though water levels were record low here, there actually seemed to be greater species diversity on this year's count (maybe the extra habitat for land birds?)."  Finding the Painted Redstart on this Count was pretty exciting!  Probably the best bird I've ever found on a CBC. ----Abbreviations used :  CBC = Christmas Bird Count.  IL = Irvine Lake.

TRIP COMMENTS: Nice sunny morning.  Upon driving north on Franklin Blvd. after just crossing the bridge I noticed to the west in a large open field approximately 100 Greater White-fronted Geese and 19 Wild Turkeys.  I pulled over and took a few photographs and began my count there.  Immediately drove into the parking lot and walked the pond area, headed east across the north cross walk and came back through the river trail only as far as the foot bridge and returned to the visitor center.  After putting away my scope and backpack I heard a large commotion from the pond area and saw all the birds take flight.  I caught a glimpse and a few shots of a bald eagle flying in a westerly direction towards I-5.  He made one pass and flew off to the north.  The pond immediately returned to normal.

TRIP COMMENTS: I have co-led this Saturday, half-day and yesterday's all-day CVBS field trip to Cosumnes River Preserve for all but one of the 19 years, when I was in Australia.  Unfortunately, John Trochet (bad back this year) was unable to take some of you to the Tall Forest, which off-limits to preserve visitors. He does a survey of that area every month and enjoys company, so you can get there if you like. I would like to thank Daniel Edelstein for being my co-leader this year and to all of you for spotting so many nice birds for the group.----This morning there was some low lying fog, but soon it burned off and we had spectacular sunny weather with little or no breeze.  It was a cool 45F when we started but much warmer by the time we headed back to Stockton in time for lunch.  We began at the ponds across from the Visitor's Center parking lot, drove over to the area along Desmond Road and then up Bruceville Road to Camp Road leading into the small airport near the penitentiary.  Every place we stopped seem to add now species to our list.  I only regret that we did not have enough time to hike to "The Point" as I did yesterday.  We had a great ending at the boardwalk with looks at two Virginia Rails and wonderful light on waterfowl and a Wilson's Snipe.----For me it was another fantastic outing in which most of the 15 participants saw all or at least most of the birds we found and/or just heard. Very nice list considering we did not walk the river trail to "The Point."----Participants:  Daniel Edelstein (my co-leader), Robert Shields (a CVBS leader trying to be off duty today,) Jim Thomas, Mike & Iris Bouchard, Thomas & Sonia Deetz, Gary Mele, Darlene Hecomovich, Anne Menke, Ellen Haningson, Gayle Hackamack, and Joan Kent.
SPECIES COMMENTS: A second year bird actually spotted by Stephen, a young birder in Sid England's group

TRIP COMMENTS: Scott Terrill, Linda Terrill, Debi Shearwater en route to San Benito Mountain. 47F, unseasonably chilly. Sunny, clear. We counted 68 Tule Elk with 4 young. Saw one coyote en route. Due to the ongoing 4 year, severe drought there was no water present that we could see. It may be that there is some water out of view of the public areas. Much of the reservoir is hidden from view on the public road. This reservoir feed the Paicines Reservoir in the central part of the county. Paicines Reservoir has been bone dry since May 2014. It sits on private property, Paicines Ranch.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Perched in one of the dead trees in what would have been a portion of the reservoir. Dry due to the ongoing 4 year drought.  One pair of bald eagles is confirmed as nesting at this location in recent years, on private property. The nest was never visible from the public road. Shearwater "discovered" the nest in a photograph made by government personnel. It was in a gray pine. Strictly enforced private property. See ominous signs posted by landowners.

SPECIES COMMENTS: My wife and I were out looking over the orchard, looked up to see an adult Bald Eagle flying across the sky!  Very large raptor, white head and tail, rest of the bird, including belly and underwings, was dark brown.  Yellow bill.  Quartering away, flapping and gliding, about 300 m away and 100 m up, in full sun with the eagle to the east of us in the low evening sun.  In view for about 20 seconds, then went out of view over the ridge, heading southeast, more or less  in the direction of Barrett Lake.  I thought it odd that BirdLog didn't ask for details on this bird which is unusual in San Diego County.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Was thought to be a juvenile Golden Eagle at first, but as it swooped over me at Boulder Bay, I got a good look at the undersides- it was a messy mottle white and brown even on the breast rather than the distinct white wing bar of the Golden Eagle. It was most likely a young Bald Eagle in it's 2nd year basic plumage.  It was seen being chased by an Osprey in the middle of the lake- starting from Hidden Bay, then east to Boulder Bay, then circling around before being chased off towards the mountains at the northeast end of the lake.

SPECIES COMMENTS: We saw the first bald eagle about 10:30 as it flew over the fish hatchery into the sun than south back over the dam.   It appeared to be a 2nd year juvenile.  It was starting to get the white head.  We had a long look at the eagle as it was soaring at a low altitude.  It was a clear morning.  We saw  the 2nd bald eagle  about noon.  It was full adult with white head & tail & dark body.  It soared over most of the park.  It soared at low altitude so we got a long look at it.  It was a clear sunny day.  We have no doubts they were bald eagles.

SPECIES COMMENTS: A first for the yard. I first noticed the bird flying low head on ~ 300 meters away. First look I thought TUVU as it was flapping low appearing to try to gain altitude. Once it stopped flapping it had no dihedral and appeared very flat winged. I then put my bins up and observed a white head and white tail, with an all brown body. It then moved away where I had good looks. I observed this adult BAEA for about 3 minutes before it moved west and out of sight.

TRIP COMMENTS: Conejo Valley Audubon field trip. Weather was windy and cold. Tide was falling, but still covering most of the mud flats when we arrived so we started at the lagoon mouth (including a seawatch) then proceeded to the night-heron roost, ballfields, perimeter to Arnold Road, and then back to the causeway. The tide had dropped by the time we made it back to the causeway, but shorebird numbers were not remarkable.

LOCALITY: Pt. Mugu Naval Air Station (restricted access)
TRIP COMMENTS: Field trip for Ventura Audubon. Tide was dropping when we arrived so we started at the causeway to look for shorebirds and then went to the lagoon mouth where we checked the lagoon and exposing sandbars for gulls, shorebirds, etc. We also did a seawatch from the lagoon mouth, which was very productive with numbers of Black-vented Shearwaters, Common Murres, and Pacific Loons. After the seawatch, we checked the night-heron roost, ballfields, and then drove the perimeter to Arnold Road.
